author: @Java.brav.Jake_1
text:
I understand why people believe that God isn't, real but from what I have seen and the proof I do not agree. Now a lot of people say that "There isn't 100% proof of God, so he can't be real." But as Cliffe Knechtle said "you do not go to the pharmacist with a testing kit to see if they have given you the right medicine. You have faith that the pharmacist gives you the right medicine to help you heal." We all have faith in everything, faith for your car to work in the morning, Faith that your friends will be loyal, Faith that you will still be alive tomorrow. We have faith in literally every aspect of our lives so to have faith in God doesn't seem as bold after that, and that is why I see it differently. 

(If you have any questions, or you think I'm wrong in anyway you can respond and I'll try to rebuttal. üí™)

author: @WhoTheLoL
text:
‚Äã‚Äã@Java.brav.Jake_1 I dont get into detailed discussions in YT comments, its counterproductive. I am open to connecting on zoom with a believer who wants to debate :).

Briefly:
What Cliffe is saying is just wordplay around equivocation of the word "faith". Yes, we don't live our lives requiring 100% proof of everything, but to say we have "faith" that a pharmacist gives me the right medicine is a blatant abuse of the word "faith". 

For the two "beliefs" (that I can go to a pharmacy and get functioning medicine, vs god existing) to be on equal footing when it comes to available evidence, and thus require similar kind of "faith", I would have to decide to go to a pharmacy X seeking medicine Y to cure illness Z, when:
- there is no evidence the pharmacy X exists
- there is no evidence the medicine Y exists 
- there is no evidence illness Z can be cured with medicine Y, that illness Z can be cured at all or that illness Z is even real and I actually have it.
- I am actually locked in shut in my home and can't actually go anywhere

You would agree that with this level of supporting evidence, believing that I can go to pharmacy X to get medicine Y to cure my illness Z would be pretty insane.

That's how much of an evidentiary gap exists between the god story and going to a pharmacy for medicine. The god story people believe in is based solely on an ancient book full of crap (6 day creation, flood, tower of babel, exodus, dude walking on water, resurrection), none of which are supported by any real evidence other than the story itself. Even if you dismiss these specific stories as metaphorical, that just means you have a book of fantastical poetry for evidence, which makes it even weaker. But even without the obviously fake stories, all versions of god belief require magic and bodyless minds at play, for which there is no evidence either. There is no reliable evidence that ANYTHING supernatural ever happened, cause all careful observations ever properly documented reveal nothing but nature doing natural stuff. The best you can find is low-probability events happening with low frequency, which is perfectly normal, but labeled as "miracles" by believers who just want to see god in everything.

If there exists a hypothesis so terribly devoid of reliable evidence in its favor that it deserves to be rejected for nothing else than intellectual integrity, then the god hypothesis is that. That's my reason for atheism - I believe in epistemic responsibility, that we are practically and morally obligated to seek accurate understanding of the universe around us, because acting on nonsense beliefs is likely to cause nonsense results that can be harmful to us and others. The god story has nothing to support its truthness except an old book of fairy tales and a pile of fallacious pseudophilosophical drivel that's accumulated over 2 millennia. The amount of reliable evidence remains zero, while the evidence to the contrary piles up.
